 policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN11-SO-000030) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective.\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen PowerShell or a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following:\n\nObject Access &gt;&gt; Other Object Access Events - Success\n\nIf the system does not audit the above, this is a finding.","rule_id_src":"SV-253321r991572_rule","group_title":"SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206","false_positives":"","uuid":"7003AA8A-6D7C-1014-87D6-B113F3819735","responsibility":"","reference_identifier":"5471","stig_uuid":"6FDFF1B9-6D7C-1014-8C20-99EC6B15618D","severity":"medium","mitigations":"","potential_impacts":"","legacy_ids":[],"status":"open","group_id":"V-253321","group_tree":{"title":"SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206","id":"V-253321"},"third_party_tools":"","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration &gt;&gt; Windows Settings &gt;&gt; Security Settings &gt;&gt; Advanced Audit Policy Configuration &gt;&gt; System Audit Policies &gt;&gt; Object Access &gt;&gt; \"Audit Other Object Access Events\" with \"Success\" selected.","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing for other object access records events related to the management of task scheduler jobs and COM+ objects.","group_id_src":"V-253321"},{"classification":"Unclassified","rule_id":"SV-253322r991572","finding_details":"Tool: cpe:/a:niwc:scc:5.14\nTime         : 2026-03-05T07:51:51\nResult: failRule Result     : Fail\nCriteria        : false (All child tests must be true. (AND))\nCriteria        :   false (One or more child tests must be true. (OR))\nTest            :     false ('Audit Other Object Access Events' is set to 'Failure')\nResult Analysis :          other_object_access_events = 'AUDIT_NONE' failed test of 'equals' compared to 'AUDIT_FAILURE' \nTest            :     false ('Audit Other Object Access Events' is set to 'Success' and 'Failure')\nResult Analysis :          other_object_access_events = 'AUDIT_NONE' failed test of 'equals' compared to 'AUDIT_SUCCESS_FAILURE' \n","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000084","rule_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit Object Access - Other Object Access Events failures.","documentable":"false","weight":"10.0","mitigation_control":"","check_content_ref":{"href":"U_MS_Windows_11_V2R7_STIG_SCAP_1-4_Benchmark-enhancedV16-oval.xml","name":"oval:mil.disa.stig.windows11:def:253322"},"security_override_guidance":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"comments":null,"ia_controls":"","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN11-SO-000030) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective.\n\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen PowerShell or a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following:\nObject Access &gt;&gt; Other Object Access Events - Failure\n\nIf the system does not audit the above, this is a finding.","rule_id_src":"SV-253322r991572_rule","group_title":"SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206","false_positives":"","uuid":"7003B015-6D7C-1014-8453-E103BE1B5515","responsibility":"","reference_identifier":"5471","stig_uuid":"6FDFF1B9-6D7C-1014-8C20-99EC6B15618D","severity":"medium","mitigations":"","potential_impacts":"","legacy_ids":[],"status":"open","group_id":"V-253322","group_tree":{"title":"SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206","id":"V-253322"},"third_party_tools":"","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration &gt;&gt; Windows Settings &gt;&gt; Security Settings &gt;&gt; Advanced Audit Policy Configuration &gt;&gt; System Audit Policies &gt;&gt; Object Access &gt;&gt; \"Audit Other Object Access Events\" with \"Failure\" selected.","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing for other object access records events related to the management of task scheduler jobs and COM+ objects.","group_id_src":"V-253322"},{"classification":"Unclassified","rule_id":"SV-253323r991583","finding_details":"Tool: cpe:/a:niwc:scc:5.14\nTime         : 2026-03-05T07:51:51\nResult: failRule Result     : Fail\nCriteria        : false (All child tests must be true. (AND))\nTest            :   true (Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings to override audit policy category settings must be set to Enabled)\nTest            :   false (Removable Storage - Failure)\nResult Analysis :        removable_storage = 'AUDIT_NONE' failed test of 'pattern match' compared to 'AUDIT_(FAILURE|SUCCESS_FAILURE)' \n","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000085","rule_title":"The system must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage failures.","documentable":"false","weight":"10.0","mitigation_control":"","check_content_ref":{"href":"U_MS_Windows_11_V2R7_STIG_SCAP_1-4_Benchmark-enhancedV16-oval2.xml","name":"oval:navy.navwar.niwcatlantic.scc.windows:def:253323"},"security_override_guidance":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"comments":null,"ia_controls":"","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN11-SO-000030) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective.\n\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\nOpen a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following. If the system does not audit the following, this is a finding:\n\nObject Access &gt;&gt; Removable Storage - Failure\n\nSome virtual machines may generate excessive audit events for access to the virtual hard disk itself when this setting is enabled. This may be set to Not Configured in such cases and would not be a finding. This must be documented with the ISSO to include mitigations such as monitoring or restricting any actual removable storage connected to the VM.","rule_id_src":"SV-253323r991583_rule","group_title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","false_positives":"","uuid":"7003B5A0-6D7C-1014-8D0C-E1048DF2EAC6","responsibility":"","reference_identifier":"5471","stig_uuid":"6FDFF1B9-6D7C-1014-8C20-99EC6B15618D","severity":"medium","mitigations":"","potential_impacts":"","legacy_ids":[],"status":"open","group_id":"V-253323","group_tree":{"title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","id":"V-253323"},"third_party_tools":"","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration &gt;&gt; Windows Settings &gt;&gt; Security Settings &gt;&gt; Advanced Audit Policy Configuration &gt;&gt; System Audit Policies &gt;&gt; Object Access &gt;&gt; \"Audit Removable Storage\" with \"Failure\" selected.","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing object access for removable media records events related to access attempts on file system objects on removable storage devices.","group_id_src":"V-253323"},{"classification":"Unclassified","rule_id":"SV-253324r991583","finding_details":"Tool: cpe:/a:niwc:scc:5.14\nTime         : 2026-03-05T07:51:51\nResult: failRule Result     : Fail\nCriteria        : false (All child tests must be true. (AND))\nTest            :   true (Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings to override audit policy category settings must be set to Enabled)\nTest            :   false (Removable Storage - Success)\nResult Analysis :        removable_storage = 'AUDIT_NONE' failed test of 'pattern match' compared to 'AUDIT_(SUCCESS|SUCCESS_FAILURE)' \n","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000090","rule_title":"The system must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage successes.","documentable":"false","weight":"10.0","mitigation_control":"","check_content_ref":{"href":"U_MS_Windows_11_V2R7_STIG_SCAP_1-4_Benchmark-enhancedV16-oval2.xml","name":"oval:navy.navwar.niwcatlantic.scc.windows:def:253324"},"security_override_guidance":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"comments":null,"ia_controls":"","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings (Windows Vista or later) to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN11-SO-000030) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective.\n\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\nOpen a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following. If the system does not audit the following, this is a finding:\n\nObject Access &gt;&gt; Removable Storage - Success\n\nSome virtual machines may generate excessive audit events for access to the virtual hard disk itself when this setting is enabled. This may be set to Not Configured in such cases and would not be a finding. This must be documented with the ISSO to include mitigations such as monitoring or restricting any actual removable storage connected to the VM.","rule_id_src":"SV-253324r991583_rule","group_title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","false_positives":"","uuid":"7003BC5F-6D7C-1014-A885-F2F7DE487819","responsibility":"","reference_identifier":"5471","stig_uuid":"6FDFF1B9-6D7C-1014-8C20-99EC6B15618D","severity":"medium","mitigations":"","potential_impacts":"","legacy_ids":[],"status":"open","group_id":"V-253324","group_tree":{"title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","id":"V-253324"},"third_party_tools":"","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration &gt;&gt; Windows Settings &gt;&gt; Security Settings &gt;&gt; Advanced Audit Policy Configuration &gt;&gt; System Audit Policies &gt;&gt; Object Access &gt;&gt; \"Audit Removable Storage\" with \"Success\" selected.","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing object access for removable media records events related to access attempts on file system objects on removable storage devices.","group_id_src":"V-253324"},{"classification":"Unclassified","rule_id":"SV-253325r991572","finding_details":"Tool: cpe:/a:niwc:scc:5.14\nTime         : 2026-03-05T07:51:51\nResult: failRule Result     : Fail\nCriteria        : false (All child tests must be true. (AND))\nCriteria        :   false (One or more child tests must be true. (OR))\nTest            :     fa